The term '''jay driver''' originated to refer to carriage drivers who drove on the incorrect side of the road. While the term may generally refer to an individual operating a vehicle in a manner not consistent with traffic laws, it was used more specifically to individuals who drive a vehicle on the incorrect side of the road. [[Merriam-Webster]] indicates that the first known use of the term is by ''The Junction City Union'' newspaper on June 28, 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/words-at-play/why-is-it-called-jaywalking|title=Why is it called Jay-Walking|last=|first=|date=|website=Merriam-Webster|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>

==Relationship to "jaywalker"==
Most sources indicate that the term "jay driver" came before "[[jaywalker]]" there being numerous article headlines from 1905 through the next decade that include the term "Jay Driver." Peter Norton's book ''Fighting Traffic'' on 78  indicates that in 1922 use of the term "jay driver" was an attempt by George A. Davies to use the known meaning of "jay walker" and apply it to drivers of vehicles.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norton |first1=Peter D |title=Fighting Traffic: The Dawn of the Motor Age in the American City |date=2008-04-18 |publisher=MIT Press |isbn=9780262141000 |pages=409 |url=https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/fighting-traffic |accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref> However, an opinion piece attributed to "A MAN BOOSTER" from the January 17, 1907 ''Salt Lake Telegram'' titled "Oh yes, there's the 'Jay Driver'" describes in it both jay walkers and jay drivers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newspapers.lib.utah.edu/details?id=19031446|title=Oh, Yes, There's the "Jay Driver"|last=|first=|date=1907-01-17|work=Salt Lake Telegram|accessdate=10 August 2018|agency=}}</ref> However, another article from November 11, 1919 in ''The Pittsburgh Gazette Times'' cites from the ''Seattle Post-Intelligencer'' the text: "There are so many jay walkers and so many jay drivers that it hardly behooves any driver to talk about jay walkers, or any walkjer to mention jay drivers," clearly demonstrating that the term existed prior to that time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1856231446?pq-origsite=summon|title=[untitled]|last=|first=|date=1919-11-11|work=The Pittsburgh Gazette Times|accessdate=10 August 2018|publisher=|issue=vol-134, iss-106|page=6|language=English}}</ref>

==In media==
A 1939 instructional video overdubbed by the voice of an official from a British agency indicates that the term was not isolated to the United States. Titled [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=peIZtd-ZJ8M School For Jay-Drivers!] the video provides an example of a motorcycle rider in Vienna failing to give the proper signal who is then required to attend a Sunday morning class in which an instructor explains what he did incorrectly and what the rules indicate he should have done.<ref>{{cite web |title=School for Jay Drivers! |url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/school-for-jay-drivers |website=British Pathe |accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>

